<head>SAFE</head>
    <list type="altnames">
<item>SECURE</item>
<item>PROTECTED</item>
<item>SHIELDED</item>
<item>SHELTERED</item>
<item>GUARDED</item>
<item>OUT OF HARM'S WAY</item>
    </list>
    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">安全</item>
        <item xml:lang="och">全</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">
<p>PEACEFUL AND NOT EASY to DAMAGE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The current general word for something being unimparied and unharmed in any way is quán 全 (ant. xiǎn 險 "imperilled").</p>
<p>2. Ān 安 (ant. wēi 危 "in imminent danger") refers to a comfortable state of unimpaired safety.</p>
<p>3. Gù 固 (ant.* sōng 鬆 "not right and impregnable") refers specifically to the provision of natural or military defenses against possible enemies.</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>安全 / 平安</p>
<p>安全 is the most general and colourless word for safety.</p>
<p>穩妥 focusses on the reliablity of a typically man-made safe state.</p>
<p>平穩</p>
<p>安穩</p>
<p>安好</p>
<p>安然</p>
<p>無恙</p>
<p>平安 focusses on the harmoniously even and unperturbed, unruffled character of what is safe.</p>
<p>安</p>
<p>安康</p>
<p>康寧</p>
<p>一路平安</p>
<p>安然無恙</p>
<p>安如泰山</p>
<p>安如磐石</p>
<p>高枕無憂</p>
<p>rough draft to BEGIN TO identify synonym group members for analysis, based on CL etc. 18.11.2003. CH ／</p>
        </div>
    </div>
